Chapter 1: The Crime Scene — My Counter That Wouldn’t Count
It was 1:47 AM. I had a simple task: build a counter that increments every second.
jsx
function Counter() {
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
useEffect(() => {
const timer = setInterval(() => {
console.log(count); // Always prints 0
setCount(count + 1); // Always sets to 1
}, 1000); return () => clearInterval(timer);
}, []); // ← This empty array is the murder weapon
return <div>{count}</div>;
}
I clicked the button. The counter showed 0. Then 1. Then… 1. Then 1. Forever.
I stared at the console. 0, 0, 0, 0...
I checked the code ten times. The logic was perfect. count + 1 should work. Right?
Wrong.
The problem wasn’t the logic. The problem was a closure — a concept I thought I understood because I’d read the definition once. I didn’t understand it at all.
